Class ReturnValue

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.Observable
      • model.ReturnValue
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    IAlgorithms, IReturnValue

    public class ReturnValue
extends java.util.Observable
implements IReturnValue
    This will be used as an example of how return values work in recursion. This is done through the factorial algorithm.

      • factorial

        public int factorial(int n)
        This is the factorial algorithm. It returns the product of an integer and all integers below it. When given a number such as 8, the factorial algorithm will calculate the value of 1*2*3...etc up until whatever the value of n is, in this case 8. So the calculation would be 1*2*3*4*5*6*7*8
        Specified by:
        factorial in interface IReturnValue
        Parameters:
        n - Any integer greater than 0 and less than 11.
        Returns:
        Returns the product of n and all integers below it
        Since:
        1.0
